postcontent: Ruger LCP .380 with Crimson Trace Laserguard. Generation 1.2. This is the second model of the Gen 1 series, which means that it has a better trigger and better sights than the very first model (which was dang near unusable).Well used, well loved.This is a great little pistol. I carried the little monster for a few years before upgrading to a larger caliber. I currently have no use for it, and have another gun on my wish list that I need funds for. I have no clue how many rounds I've ran through it (quite a few), but it has never once jammed or had a malfunction of any sort, even with reloads. Off a bench it'll shoot better, but that's not what this gun is made for. Crimson Trace laser works fine and has a new battery. These lasers are extremely handy for a pocket pistol with admittedly minimal sights. Also very handy for dry fire practice (the laser lets you easily see if you're twitching or moving when you pull the trigger).Comes with original box for the gun (including the stuff that came with it, like the manual and the little zipper bag) and the CT laser, 3 mags, and a DeSantos Superfly pocket holster. Fits right in the back pocket of jeans, and won't tilt or rotate on you with this holster. Very nice and simple design.Asking $350 for the whole package. I know that there are a couple of newer models of the LCP currently, but a new setup like this would cost you over $550 (~$230/ gun, ~$200/laser, $40/holster $50/mags). To get the LCP/CT package new (using this model LCP) at sportsmans its $480, with one mag and no holster).Call or text REDACTED if you're interested.
